00:46:07.010 --> 00:46:11.200
I'm guessing all of us have been
in jobs where we sit in a cube.

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:14.610
We work on a PowerPoint
slide, and we throw it

00:46:14.610 --> 00:46:16.610
over the cubicle
wall to our manager,

00:46:16.610 --> 00:46:17.951
and we never see it again.

00:46:17.951 --> 00:46:20.200
We don't know what worked
we don't have an opportunity

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:22.674
to innovate or experiment.

00:46:22.674 --> 00:46:24.340
When you don't have
purpose in your job,

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:27.130
it's usually because you can't
see the impact of your work.

00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:29.280
Can you go and see how
it's making a difference

00:46:29.280 --> 00:46:30.660
to organizations?

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:34.530
So examples of both-- play,
on the Toyota production

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:38.050
line-- you would think that an
assembly line job manufacturing

00:46:38.050 --> 00:46:40.180
cars would have
very little play.

00:46:40.180 --> 00:46:42.950
But Toyota enables their
people to actually come up

00:46:42.950 --> 00:46:46.220
with new tools or new ways of
doing their job while they're

00:46:46.220 --> 00:46:47.222
working on the line.

00:46:47.222 --> 00:46:48.680
And they have a
group of folks that

00:46:48.680 --> 00:46:51.220
will go and make that tool
when they have an idea

00:46:51.220 --> 00:46:53.260
and bring it back
so they can test it.

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:55.530
That's a way of having
play in that job.

00:46:55.530 --> 00:46:58.470
Purpose, for example--
at Medtronic,

00:46:58.470 --> 00:47:03.140
which creates a lot
of health care tools,

00:47:03.140 --> 00:47:05.880
they actually go and see those
tools in action in surgery

00:47:05.880 --> 00:47:07.910
so that they can see the
impact of their work,

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:09.160
and also it inspires play.

00:47:09.160 --> 00:47:11.426
They can see what's
working, what's not working.

00:47:11.426 --> 00:47:11.800
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:12.966
LINDSAY MCGREGOR: Thank you.

00:47:14.550 --> 00:47:16.780
AUDIENCE: What if
you have reports

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:19.660
who just states that
his motivation is

00:47:19.660 --> 00:47:22.930
purely a reward-based
or praised-base,

00:47:22.930 --> 00:47:26.140
so he cares about whether
managers think he's doing

00:47:26.140 --> 00:47:29.196
a good job and whether the
company is paying him enough

00:47:29.196 --> 00:47:30.820
and doesn't understand
other people who

00:47:30.820 --> 00:47:33.099
are motivated by play?

00:47:33.099 --> 00:47:35.140
NEEL DOSHI: And it's
someone that's on your team,

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:36.913
or someone that is
managing a team?

00:47:36.913 --> 00:47:38.412
AUDIENCE: Let's
just say that I have

00:47:38.412 --> 00:47:40.680
a friend who has
someone on their team

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:41.930
to pretend that's somebody--

00:47:41.930 --> 00:47:43.340
NEEL DOSHI: A lot of
people have friends

00:47:43.340 --> 00:47:44.340
I notice in these talks.

00:47:47.510 --> 00:47:49.160
What we've noticed
in our research

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:54.490
is people are notoriously bad
at self-identifying how motives

00:47:54.490 --> 00:47:56.240
drive their own performance.

00:47:56.240 --> 00:48:00.264
So what we see a lot is
organizations do the following.

00:48:00.264 --> 00:48:01.680
They know there's
something that's

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:03.490
not working with their culture.

00:48:03.490 --> 00:48:06.172
They don't know that play,
purpose, potential even exists.

00:48:06.172 --> 00:48:07.880
So they asked their
people, what would it

00:48:07.880 --> 00:48:09.610
take to make this
culture better?

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:12.970
And their people say,
less work and more money.

00:48:12.970 --> 00:48:14.220
That's a very common practice.

00:48:14.220 --> 00:48:16.219
We see it play out over
and over and over again.

00:48:16.219 --> 00:48:18.230
People are pretty
bad self identifying

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:19.610
their own known motives.

00:48:19.610 --> 00:48:22.490
So when our work, we don't
advocate asking your people

00:48:22.490 --> 00:48:23.590
what they want, actually.

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:26.820
It's not particularly helpful
because play, purpose,

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:30.070
potential drive
performance consistently.

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:32.860
It is essentially
human instinct.

00:48:32.860 --> 00:48:35.780
So even if you're person
says, this is what I want,

00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:38.990
this is what people
want, it doesn't actually

00:48:38.990 --> 00:48:41.160
change what actually
drives performance.

00:48:41.160 --> 00:48:42.599
And when we have
folks like that,

00:48:42.599 --> 00:48:44.390
we've often been brought
into organizations

00:48:44.390 --> 00:48:47.950
because an executive
will say, you know, Neel,

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:49.990
our CEO is a bit toxic.

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:51.740
Like, this is what he believes.

00:48:51.740 --> 00:48:53.520
People just operate
on sticks and carrots.

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:56.530
What we normally do with those
folks is we share with them

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:59.970
the science, the data, the
research, and the language,

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:01.324
the tools, the framework.

00:49:01.324 --> 00:49:02.990
And sometimes we'll
make that CEO get up

00:49:02.990 --> 00:49:05.760
and do math in front
of his colleagues.

00:49:05.760 --> 00:49:08.041
And by the time that's
done, they get it.

00:49:08.041 --> 00:49:08.984
They get it.

00:49:08.984 --> 00:49:10.400
LINDSAY MCGREGOR:
So, for example,

00:49:10.400 --> 00:49:13.910
we've been able to measure
TOMO among hedge fund portfolio

00:49:13.910 --> 00:49:16.800
managers and proven that TOMO
is what's driving their highest

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:19.090
performers, not money.

00:49:19.090 --> 00:49:21.890
Or there's been research done
in investment banking, where

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:24.515
maybe the reason you go into
that industry is for the money.

00:49:24.515 --> 00:49:27.140
But when you look at who is the
highest performing once they're

00:49:27.140 --> 00:49:29.910
actually there, it's who's
getting up on Wednesday

00:49:29.910 --> 00:49:31.510
morning and doing the best work.

00:49:31.510 --> 00:49:33.470
It's the person that's finding
the play and the purpose

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:34.280
and the potential.

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:36.321
AUDIENCE: OK, so your
recommendation to my friend

00:49:36.321 --> 00:49:37.489
is show him the data?

00:49:37.489 --> 00:49:39.780
NEEL DOSHI: Yeah, and help
them understand that there's

00:49:39.780 --> 00:49:44.125
a frame of thinking that's
more nuanced than just poke

00:49:44.125 --> 00:49:45.385
and prod your people.

00:49:45.385 --> 00:49:48.140
And once people understand
that frame of thinking,

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:49.524
they start to self identify.

00:49:49.524 --> 00:49:51.440
They start to see it in
the world around them.

00:49:54.824 --> 00:49:56.240
AUDIENCE: Good-- thank you.

00:49:56.240 --> 00:49:57.740
AUDIENCE: So my
question is related

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:03.110
to the general corporate
way of managing employees.

00:50:03.110 --> 00:50:06.160
So across several companies,
working for more than decade,

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:08.740
now what I've seen is that,
all right, those who do well

00:50:08.740 --> 00:50:13.810
are rewarded, but indirect
ones and those who do worse

00:50:13.810 --> 00:50:18.220
are actually rewarded with
more specific objectives

00:50:18.220 --> 00:50:20.530
that they have to
complete within the time.

00:50:20.530 --> 00:50:22.910
If they don't, then
they're thrown out

00:50:22.910 --> 00:50:24.110
or something like that.

00:50:24.110 --> 00:50:28.240
So typically, both
are doing indirect,

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:33.070
like those who did very
poorly, now have hey,

00:50:33.070 --> 00:50:36.260
your job will be turned gone if
you don't do this, this, this.

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:37.740
You have to do exactly that.

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:39.450
So high on tactical.

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:42.070
And those who do well,
oh, you did so well.

00:50:42.070 --> 00:50:42.862
Here's your reward.

00:50:42.862 --> 00:50:44.444
That's what happens
with the toddlers.

00:50:44.444 --> 00:50:46.740
They were probably taught,
it's not playful anymore.

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:47.930
I'm getting something.

00:50:47.930 --> 00:50:50.410
Maybe I don't want it.

00:50:50.410 --> 00:50:52.260
So what's going on?

00:50:52.260 --> 00:50:54.930
Are we-- am I in a company,
which is completely bogus?

00:50:54.930 --> 00:50:57.280
Have I been company which
are completely bogus,

00:50:57.280 --> 00:50:59.530
and they have no clue
what is going on?

00:50:59.530 --> 00:51:01.805
Or why is that like that?

00:51:01.805 --> 00:51:03.430
LINDSAY MCGREGOR:
It's a good question.

00:51:03.430 --> 00:51:07.160
So money or paying people
is not intrinsically

00:51:07.160 --> 00:51:09.450
a bad things or
intrinsically a good thing.

00:51:09.450 --> 00:51:11.800
It matter is if your
bonus or those rewards

00:51:11.800 --> 00:51:15.030
are changing the reason
why you're working.

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:17.950
So a counterintuitive example
is we measured the sales

00:51:17.950 --> 00:51:21.720
commissions and to see how sales
commissions affected somebody's

00:51:21.720 --> 00:51:22.494
TOMO.

00:51:22.494 --> 00:51:23.910
And before this
talk, you probably

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:26.280
thought, oh, sales
commissions are a great thing.

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:28.071
At this point in time,
you might be saying,

00:51:28.071 --> 00:51:30.616
sales commissions are
probably a terrible thing.

00:51:30.616 --> 00:51:32.990
But what it turns out, is
that-- excuse me, contact lens.

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:37.780
I think you need to take over.

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:39.030
My contact lens is falling out.

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:41.405
NEEL DOSHI: So what it turns
out-- adaptive performance--

00:51:41.405 --> 00:51:44.349
where it turns out is
that-- there you go, right?

00:51:44.349 --> 00:51:45.640
LINDSAY MCGREGOR: Yeah, exactly

00:51:45.640 --> 00:51:48.014
NEEL DOSHI: --is that when
you have somebody with a sales

00:51:48.014 --> 00:51:50.510
commission who very much
believes that their work is

00:51:50.510 --> 00:51:52.390
doing the best thing
for their customers,

00:51:52.390 --> 00:51:54.840
that sales commission
actually increases their TOMO.

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:55.990
Because they're not doing it
for the commission anymore.

00:51:55.990 --> 00:51:57.050
They actually believe
in what they're doing.

00:51:57.050 --> 00:51:58.350
The commission is just gravy.

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:01.389
Now your question is, why are
there so few great cultures?

00:52:01.389 --> 00:52:03.680
Like, I've kind of flipped
your question around, right?

00:52:03.680 --> 00:52:05.970
So many of the organizations
you work with were using

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:09.262
sticks and carrots to motivate
high and low performers.

00:52:09.262 --> 00:52:10.720
Well, the problem
is, is that, one,

00:52:10.720 --> 00:52:13.299
this research is actually
pretty cutting edge.

00:52:13.299 --> 00:52:14.840
The research that
we've come up with,

00:52:14.840 --> 00:52:19.430
this frame, this thinking, this
data, is only a few years old.

00:52:19.430 --> 00:52:21.050
We both had MBAs.

00:52:21.050 --> 00:52:23.430
We both went to big
consulting firms.

00:52:23.430 --> 00:52:28.320
The practices that we learned
and executed were low TOMO.

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:29.110
And we try it.

00:52:29.110 --> 00:52:31.950
You get a very short
term blip in performance

00:52:31.950 --> 00:52:34.720
because tactical
performance is quick.

00:52:34.720 --> 00:52:36.780
You don't notice that
what you just did actually

00:52:36.780 --> 00:52:38.300
destroyed adaptive performance.

00:52:38.300 --> 00:52:39.380
You don't notice it
because you never

00:52:39.380 --> 00:52:40.840
had a language for
adaptive performance.

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:41.798
It's harder to measure.

00:52:41.798 --> 00:52:42.720
It's harder to see.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:44.510
And if it did go
down, you didn't even

00:52:44.510 --> 00:52:45.533
know what caused that.

00:52:45.533 --> 00:52:47.574
And so you kind of throw
your hands up in the air

00:52:47.574 --> 00:52:50.092
and you say, oh, it's
just because we're big.

00:52:50.092 --> 00:52:51.890
Well, Southwest is big.

00:52:51.890 --> 00:52:53.970
Nordstrom is big.

00:52:53.970 --> 00:52:55.680
It's not that.

00:52:55.680 --> 00:52:58.890
It's that we just simply didn't
understand TOMO and adaptive

00:52:58.890 --> 00:53:00.841
performance.

00:53:00.841 --> 00:53:03.529
LINDSAY MCGREGOR:
Any other questions?

00:53:03.529 --> 00:53:05.320
All right, thank you,
everybody for coming.

00:53:05.320 --> 00:53:06.070
We really appreciate it.

00:53:06.070 --> 00:53:07.730
NEEL DOSHI: It's a
pleasure to be here.

